4. Are there more carnivores or herbivores represented in the data? Make a plot that shows the number in each trophic guild.

ggplot(data=homerange,
       mapping=aes(x=trophic.guild))+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(fill=trophic.guild), color="black")+
  labs(title="Number of Animals in Each Trophic Guild", x="Trophic Guild")

There are more carnivores than herbivores represented in this data.

5. Which herbivorous mammals have homeranges greater than 1,000,000 m? Show only the common name, order, mean homerange size, and mean body mass. Arrange the data in descending order by homerange size and show only the top 10 species.

homerange %>% 
  filter(trophic.guild=="herbivore") %>% 
  filter(class=="mammalia") %>% 
  select(common.name, order, mean.hra.m2, mean.mass.g) %>% 
  filter(mean.hra.m2>1000000) %>% 
  slice_max(mean.hra.m2, n=10)

8. Is there a relationship between body mass and homerange size? Make a scatterplot to show this relationship. Be sure to include appropriate labels and a title.

ggplot(data=homerange,
       mapping=aes(x=log10.mass, y=log10.hra))+
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=class))+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=T)+
  labs(title="Body Mass vs. Homerange Size", x="Body Mass (log10(g))", y="Homerange Size (log10(m^2))")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

There is a positive relationship between body mass and homerange size.

10. Do one additional exploratory analysis of your choice. Before writing the code, write the question you are trying to answer. The question should be biologically meaningful and appropriate for the data. It must include at least one filter(), select(), and arrange().

One may assume that the larger an animal is, the larger their prey needs to be to acquire enough energy and nutrients. However, is this truly the case? Is there a positive association between carnivorous predator mass and their corresponding prey mass in this data?

carnivore_prey <- homerange %>% 
  filter(trophic.guild=="carnivore") %>% 
  select(class, log10.mass, preymass) %>% 
  arrange(desc(preymass))
carnivore_prey
## # A tibble: 342  3
##    class    log10.mass preymass
##    <chr>         <dbl>    <dbl>
##  1 mammalia       5.05  130233.
##  2 mammalia       4.48   57547.
##  3 mammalia       4.68   30234.
##  4 mammalia       4.11   18055.
##  5 mammalia       4.01   10522.
##  6 mammalia       4.48    4065.
##  7 mammalia       4.04    3891.
##  8 reptilia       3.01    2684.
##  9 mammalia       4.00    1527.
## 10 mammalia       3.56    1110.
## #  332 more rows
ggplot(data=carnivore_prey,
       mapping=aes(x=log10.mass, y=preymass))+
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=class))+
  scale_y_log10()+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=T)+
  labs(title="Predator Mass vs. Prey Mass", x="Predator Mass (log10(g))", y="Prey Mass (log10(g))")

## (`geom_point()`).

There is a positive relationship between carnivorous predator mass and prey mass in this data.
